# Locomotion Engine — Book 05 (Draft)
## Charm Systems & Emergent Design

---

# 🧠 Philosophy

Charm is not created by large features.

Charm emerges from:
- small systems
- consistent rules
- visible consequences
- restraint

The goal is to create a game that feels:

> “alive, reactive, and deeper than expected”

---

# 🎯 Core Design Rule

> Systems should be discoverable, not explained.

Players should notice things naturally over time.

---

# 🧬 Category 1 — Unit Identity Systems

## 1. Persistent Unit Memory
Units can carry subtle identity across waves.

- survivors gain minor traits
- visual indicators (scars, tint, posture)
- optional rare “returning enemy” moments

---

## 2. Trait-Based Visual Changes
Stats influence appearance:

- fast → lean, lighter colours
- tank → bulkier, heavier armour
- elite → glow / accents

---

## 3. Variant Weighting
Some parts are rarer:

- uncommon helmets
- rare weapons
- subtle rarity increases over time

---

## 4. Micro Naming (Optional / Rare)
Occasionally:
- enemies generate simple names
- appears only on hover or zoom

---

# ⚔️ Category 2 — Combat Feedback Systems

## 5. Damage Numbers (Smart)
- aggregated values
- crits highlighted
- limited concurrent display

---

## 6. Kill Feedback
- small pop or burst
- distinct from damage

---

## 7. Status Effects (Visual First)
- poison drip
- burn flicker
- stun sparks

---

## 8. Impact Persistence
- arrows remain briefly
- scorch marks linger
- hit direction slightly visible

---

# 💀 Category 3 — Battlefield Memory

## 9. Corpse Lifecycle System
Stages:
- fresh → decay → bones → gone

---

## 10. Corpse Cap System
- max corpse count (configurable)
- oldest removed first

---

## 11. Environmental Staining
- blood/dirt tint ground slightly
- fades over time

---

## 12. Biome-Based Decay
- swamp → faster decay
- snow → slower decay

---

# 🧠 Category 4 — Behaviour Systems

## 13. Micro Behaviour Variations
- hesitation near damage
- clustering behind tanks
- occasional rush behaviour

---

## 14. Panic State (Rare)
- low HP → flee briefly or erratic movement

---

## 15. Opportunistic Behaviour
- some units move faster when path clears

---

## 16. Elite Mutation (Rare)
- unit evolves mid-wave
- visual + stat shift

---

# 🎲 Category 5 — Rare Events

## 17. Gold Carrier Unit
- steals gold if escapes
- visually distinct

---

## 18. Broken Formation
- wave slightly desyncs
- feels more organic

---

## 19. Survivor Evolution
- surviving unit returns later stronger

---

## 20. Mini-Boss Spawn
- emerges from regular unit pool

---

# 🌍 Category 6 — World Systems

## 21. Subtle Background Motion
- fog drift
- embers
- ambient particles

---

## 22. Tower Wear (Optional)
- towers visually change slightly over time

---

## 23. Audio Reinforcement (Future)
- subtle audio cues for:
  - crits
  - deaths
  - elites

---

# 🎮 Category 7 — Player Perception Systems

## 24. Zoom-Based Detail
- more detail visible when zoomed in
- encourages inspection

---

## 25. Hidden Information Layer
- deeper stats not shown immediately
- optional discovery

---

## 26. Delayed Understanding
- player notices patterns before being told

---

# 🧩 Category 8 — System Interactions

## 27. Systems Affect Systems
- fire → faster corpse decay
- poison → lingering ground effect

---

## 28. Stacking Effects
- multiple small systems combine into larger moments

---

## 29. Visual Priority Rules
- ensure readability:
  - enemies > effects > corpses > background

---

# 🎯 Category 9 — Restraint Systems

## 30. Caps & Limits
Everything has a cap:
- corpses
- damage numbers
- effects

---

## 31. Controlled Chaos
Chaos increases with waves but:
- always readable
- never overwhelming

---

# 🧠 Final Principle

> The player should never feel the system is random.

Instead:

> It should feel like everything is intentional, even when procedural.

---

# 🚀 Outcome

When these systems combine:

- early game → clean, simple  
- mid game → varied, interesting  
- late game → chaotic but meaningful  

The player experience becomes:

> “I didn’t notice when it got complex… but now it is.”

---

# 💡 Summary

Locomotion’s charm comes from:

- persistence
- subtle variation
- emergent behaviour
- visual storytelling

Not from feature count.

---

# 🧭 Future Expansion

These systems should be:

- modular
- optional
- progressively enabled

---

> Charm is not a feature.  
> It is the result of systems interacting over time.

